The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, Dec. 19: The government plans to spend Rs 1.47 lakh crore in addition to the provisions made in this years budget to recharge the economy. As part of the extra spending, Parliament today passed a second supplementary demand for grants of Rs 42,480 crore. Much of the money will be spent to stimulate demand. The public expenditure is being raised to make the supply side more attractive, home minister P. Chidambaram said.                             
	 Calcutta, Dec. 19: The indefinite strike by the jute industry was called off today following a settlement reached in New Delhi. According to the terms of the settlement, permanent workers of the jute mills will get an ad hoc payment of Rs 500 per month against dues on dearness allowance.                             
	 Vijayawada, Dec. 19: Truckers across the country will go on an indefinite strike from January 5, 2009, if the government fails to accept their demands, said P. Gopal Naidu, vice-president of All India Motor Transport Congress, south zone.                             
	 Ahmedabad, Dec. 19: Civil aviation minister Praful Patel said private airlines would slash air fares in January. We will see air fares coming down in January after the reduction in ATF prices, he said.                            
	 New Delhi, Dec. 19: Ranbaxy and Daiichi Sankyo have jointly announced the reconstitution of the Gurgaon-based companys board of directors. Ranbaxy CEO and managing director Malvinder Mohan Singh will assume the charge of chairman of the board.                            
	 New Delhi, Dec. 19: Parsvnath Developers has put on hold 12 SEZ projects because of a credit crunch. We have put on hold some big projects where we need to invest a large sum of money, Parsvnath chairman Pradeep Jain said.                            
	 New Delhi, Dec. 19: Honda Siel Cars India may not renew contracts of temporary workers, but has ruled out any permanent job cuts.                                                                                                                         
